TY  - JOUR
T1  - Forecasting international growth rates using Bayesian shrinkage and other procedures
AU  - Zellner, Arnold
AU  - Hong, Chansik
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 40
IS  - 1
SP  - 183
EP  - 202
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/01/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(89)90036-5
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407689900365
AB  - Forecasts of eighteen countries' annual output growth rates, 1974–1984, are computed using an autoregressive model containing leading indicator variables and various forecasting procedures. It is found that Bayesian shrinkage forecasting techniques produced improved forecasts in terms of an out-of-sample root-mean-square criterion relative to those provided by three naive models and by autoregressive models with and without leading indicator variables. The precision of our forecasts compares favorably with that of OECD forecasts derived from complicated econometric ‘structural’ macroeconometric models and subjected to judgmental adjustments. Work to rationalize our forecasting models in terms of macroeconomic theory is in progress.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - An econometric analysis of the bank credit scoring problem
AU  - Boyes, William J.
AU  - Hoffman, Dennis L.
AU  - Low, Stuart A.
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 40
IS  - 1
SP  - 3
EP  - 14
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/01/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(89)90026-2
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407689900262
AB  - Most credit assessment models used in practice are based on simple credit scoring functions estimated by discriminant analysis. These functions are designed to distinguish whether or not applicants belong to the population of ‘would be’ defaulters. We suggest that the traditional view that emphasizes default probability is too narrow. Our model of credit assessment focuses on expected earnings. We demonstrate how maximum likelihood estimates of default probabilities can be obtained from a bivariate ‘censored probit’ framework using a ‘choice-based’ sample originally intended for discriminant analysis. The paper concludes with recommendations for combining these default probability estimates with other parameters of the loan earnings process to obtain a more meaningful model of credit assessment.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Trend reversion in real output and unemployment
AU  - Clark, Peter K.
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 40
IS  - 1
SP  - 15
EP  - 32
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/01/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(89)90027-4
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407689900274
AB  - Quarterly data on aggregate real output and unemployment in the United States, Canada, United Kingdom, France, West Germany and Japan are decomposed into independent stationary and non-stationary components using the Kalman filter and maximum likelihood. In four of the six countries, a large, persistent stationary component is apparent, indicating a substantial amount of reversion to a smooth growth trend. In each case, this estimated stationary component is closely related to the estimated stationary component of the unemployment rate. For the United States, an expanded bivariate model indicates that independence of the two output components is a reasonable assumption.
ER  - 

